    title: 'Trust the Process',
    desc: 'Stop stressing about the future. Your season is coming.',
    why_it_matters: 'Anxiety about the future is one of the biggest things that blocks girls from enjoying their present and doing their best work. Learning to trust the process is a superpower that top athletes, entrepreneurs, and leaders all share.',
    key_facts: ['Anxiety about the future activates the same brain response as physical danger.', 'Research shows that people who focus on the process — not just the outcome — perform better and feel happier.', 'Delayed gratification is one of the strongest predictors of long-term success.', 'You cannot control outcomes, but you can always control your effort and attitude.'],
    sections: [
      { title: 'What Does "Trust the Process" Actually Mean?', content: 'It means shifting your focus from where you want to end up to what you are doing right now. The process is the daily habits, the small decisions, the quiet work nobody sees. When you trust the process, you stop asking "why isn\'t it happening yet?" and start asking "what can I do today?"' },
      { title: 'Why We Obsess Over the Future', content: 'Our brains are wired to plan ahead. But in modern life, that same wiring can turn into constant "what if" thinking. Social media makes it worse because you see everyone else\'s highlight reel and think you\'re behind. You are not behind. You are on your own timeline.' },
      { title: 'The Difference Between Planning and Worrying', content: 'Planning is productive. Worrying is unproductive. The rule: if you can do something about it right now, do it. If you can\'t, release it. Write it down, pray about it, talk to someone — then let it go and get back to your process.' },
      { title: 'How to Actually Trust the Process', content: 'First, define YOUR process — what daily habits move you toward your goal? Second, track your inputs, not just your outputs. Did you study? Did you practice? Did you show up? Third, celebrate small wins.' },
    ],
    activities: ['Write down one big goal you have. Now list 3–5 daily habits that would move you toward it. Post this somewhere you can see it every day.', 'Think of something you\'ve been anxious about. Ask yourself: Can I do something about this right now? If yes, write one action step. If no, release it.', 'Research one person you admire. Find out how long it took them to "make it" and what their process looked like.'],
